### Footnotes

<span id="fn_1771"></span>[355:1](sbe0856.htm#fr_1778.md) Cf. Gîtâ, [p.
45](sbe0804.htm#page_45.md).

<span id="fn_1772"></span>[355:2](sbe0856.htm#fr_1779.md) All this is
action, the fruit of which is perishable; the fruit of knowledge, on the
other hand, is everlasting.

<span id="fn_1773"></span>[355:3](sbe0857.htm#fr_1780.md) Literally, time;
it seems, however, to stand for the vicissitudes of worldly life. Cf.
*S*vetâ*s*vatara, p. 283. The body is called 'wheel of time' at [p.
53](sbe0805.htm#page_53.md) supra, but Ar*g*una Mi*s*ra there says 'it is
the wheel which causes the rotation of the wheel of time.'

<span id="fn_1774"></span>[355:4](sbe0857.htm#fr_1781.md) The cause of its
being large in dimensions, Ar*g*una Mi*s*ra; the supporting pillar,
Nîlaka*nth*a. I prefer the former, and take the sense to be that worldly
life is co-extensive with the operations or 'fancies' of the mind.

<span id="fn_1775"></span>[355:5](sbe0857.htm#fr_1782.md) What is outside
the elements, the physical manifestations of Prak*ri*ti, is beyond the
domain of worldly life.

<span id="fn_1776"></span>[355:6](sbe0857.htm#fr_1783.md) The possession of
'home' is equivalent to a dwelling in the midst of worldly life. Hence
the idea of homelessness at inter alia Gîtâ, pp.
[101](sbe0814.htm#page_101)-[103](sbe0815.htm#page_103.md).

<span id="fn_1777"></span>[356:1](sbe0857.htm#fr_1784.md) This means, I
presume, that worldly life is conditioned, so to say, by space and time.
See [p. 343](sbe0854.htm#page_343.md) supra.

<span id="fn_1778"></span>[356:2](sbe0857.htm#fr_1785.md) I. e. the cause
of the rotation, Nîlaka*nth*a.

<span id="fn_1779"></span>[356:3](sbe0857.htm#fr_1786.md) I. e.
unintelligent.

<span id="fn_1780"></span>[356:4](sbe0857.htm#fr_1787.md) Now takes the
form of a man, now of an animal, and then of some other thing,
Nîlaka*nth*a. I think, however, that the meaning is, that it is not
alike to all; different persons are in different states in this world.

<span id="fn_1781"></span>[356:5](sbe0857.htm#fr_1788.md) Ar*g*una Mi*s*ra
says this means that it is the cause of the movements in all the worlds.
That is the sense I extract from his words, which are not quite clear,
lokânâm sam*k*ara*n*e hetus. The rendering in the text follows
Nîlaka*nth*a.

<span id="fn_1782"></span>[356:6](sbe0857.htm#fr_1789.md) I. e., I presume,
that which retards the revolutions of the 'wheel.' Instead of 'penance,'
Nîlaka*nth*a's reading is 'the, quality of darkness.'

<span id="fn_1783"></span>[356:7](sbe0857.htm#fr_1790.md) Cf.
Sâ<u>n</u>khya-kârikâ, p. 13, and Vâkaspati's commentary thereon.

<span id="fn_1784"></span>[356:8](sbe0857.htm#fr_1791.md) 'Animated,'
Nîlaka*nth*a. Egoism is the cause of the world, and of all knowledge of
it. Cf. Sâ<u>n</u>khya-kârikâ, p. 24.

<span id="fn_1785"></span>[356:9](sbe0857.htm#fr_1792.md) The text here is
unsatisfactory. I follow Nîlaka*nth*a, who says 'vexations = those
arising from not obtaining what is desired.'

<span id="fn_1786"></span>[357:1](sbe0857.htm#fr_1793.md) Revolves in the
midst of, = lives upon, is fed by, Nîlaka*nth*a.

<span id="fn_1787"></span>[357:2](sbe0857.htm#fr_1794.md) I. e. the organs
of action, I presume.

<span id="fn_1788"></span>[357:3](sbe0857.htm#fr_1795.md) The more
attachments one has, the more one is tied down to worldly life, and the
more comprehensive such life becomes.

<span id="fn_1789"></span>[357:4](sbe0857.htm#fr_1796.md) Avarice is
coveting another's wealth when one has one's own; desire is the wish for
that which one has not.

<span id="fn_1790"></span>[357:5](sbe0857.htm#fr_1797.md) Nîlaka*nth*a
reads 'vi*k*itra,' which he renders to mean diversified, as being made
up of the three qualities, ignorance there being the same thing as
Prak*ri*ti, which is probably a better sense altogether than that
obtainable from Ar*g*una Mi*s*ra's reading.

<span id="fn_1791"></span>[357:6](sbe0857.htm#fr_1798.md) Which moves by
attachment to eternal pleasures, &c., Nîlaka*nth*a. See [p.
300](sbe0842.htm#page_300.md) supra.

<span id="fn_1792"></span>[357:7](sbe0857.htm#fr_1799.md) I. e. all the
world developed from Prakriti--a common phrase.

<span id="fn_1793"></span>[357:8](sbe0857.htm#fr_1800.md) This is
Nîlaka*nth*a's forced meaning. But the text here is doubtful. Perhaps
the sense is 'in which production and dissolution are going on
unchecked.'

<span id="fn_1794"></span>[357:9](sbe0857.htm#fr_1801.md) See [p.
344](sbe0854.htm#page_344.md) note. For the last word, the variant here is
sthâpayet, make steady or stop.

<span id="fn_1795"></span>[358:1](sbe0857.htm#fr_1802.md) I. e. the causes
of the revolution and stoppage, Nîlaka*nth*a.

<span id="fn_1796"></span>[358:2](sbe0857.htm#fr_1803.md) Impressions of
previous actions, delusions, &c. And see [p. 247](sbe0831.htm#page_247.md)
supra.

<span id="fn_1797"></span>[358:3](sbe0857.htm#fr_1804.md) I. e. the
Samnyâsin.

<span id="fn_1798"></span>[358:4](sbe0857.htm#fr_1805.md) *S*âstra. Cf.
Gîtâ, [p. 117](sbe0818.htm#page_117.md).

<span id="fn_1799"></span>[358:5](sbe0857.htm#fr_1806.md) 'Such is the
eternal fame,' literally.

<span id="fn_1800"></span>[358:6](sbe0857.htm#fr_1807.md) I. e. on whom the
Vedic rites or Sa*m*skâras are duly performed. And see Gîtâ, [p.
122](sbe0820.htm#page_122.md).

<span id="fn_1801"></span>[358:7](sbe0857.htm#fr_1808.md) I. e. one of the
three higher castes.

<span id="fn_1802"></span>[358:8](sbe0857.htm#fr_1809.md) The original is
the technical word for the return of a Brahma*k*ârin after finishing his
studies. He is describing the 'householder.'

<span id="fn_1803"></span>[358:9](sbe0857.htm#fr_1810.md) I. e. following
the rule of conduct sanctioned by the good.

<span id="fn_1804"></span>[358:10](sbe0857.htm#fr_1811.md) Vide Williams'
Dictionary, s.v. mahâya*g*ña; Â*s*valâyana G*ri*hya III, 1, 3; Manu II,
69; IV, 21.

<span id="fn_1805"></span>[358:11](sbe0857.htm#fr_1812.md) Cf. Gîtâ, [p.
62](sbe0806.htm#page_62.md); a guest must always be fed, and unless he is
satisfied the host must not eat. Cf. *S*ânti Parvan (Moksha), chap. 192,
st. 15; Manu III, 106; Âpastamba II, 3, 7, 3.

<span id="fn_1806"></span>[359:1](sbe0857.htm#fr_1813.md) The same word as
at Gîtâ, [p. 114](sbe0817.htm#page_114.md), there rendered 'vain activity.'

<span id="fn_1807"></span>[359:2](sbe0857.htm#fr_1814.md) Cf. Âpastamba II,
1, 1, 2 seq.

<span id="fn_1808"></span>[359:3](sbe0857.htm#fr_1815.md) Cf. Manu IV, 36;
Âpastamba II, 1, 1, 15.

<span id="fn_1809"></span>[359:4](sbe0857.htm#fr_1816.md) These are the
well-known six duties of Brâhma*n*as as specified by Manu and others.
See the discussion of this point in the Introduction.

<span id="fn_1810"></span>[359:5](sbe0857.htm#fr_1817.md) Another reading
is 'gifts from an untainted (source).'

<span id="fn_1811"></span>[359:6](sbe0857.htm#fr_1818.md) What is the exact
meaning of this here? I suppose the meaning is that the performance of
them is a pure performance of duty; the others are duties the
performance of which supplies ones own wants, and is therefore
interested. Cf. Gautama X, 1 and 2.

<span id="fn_1812"></span>[359:7](sbe0857.htm#fr_1819.md) I. e. omission or
mistake in performance.

